---

### Key Features

| Feature | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| **`instructions`** | System prompt for the agent |
| **`tools`** | Tools the agent can use |
| **`stopWhen`** | When to stop the loop (e.g., `stepCountIs(5)`, `hasNoToolCalls`) |
| **`prepareStep`** | Modify messages/tools before each step |
| **`onStepFinish`** | Callback after each tool execution |
| **`onFinish`** | Callback when agent completes |

---

### Type Safety Bonus

```typescript
import { InferAgentUIMessage } from 'ai';

// Infer the exact UIMessage type from your agent
export type MediaAgentUIMessage = InferAgentUIMessage<typeof mediaAgent>;

// Now in your React component:
const { messages } = useChat<MediaAgentUIMessage>();

// TypeScript knows exactly what tool parts exist:
message.parts.map(part => {
  if (part.type === 'tool-generateImageWithPolling') {
    // part.input and part.output are fully typed!
  }
});
```

---

### When to Use It

| Use `ToolLoopAgent` | Use manual `streamText` |
|---------------------|------------------------|
| Reusable agent definition | One-off streaming |
| Multiple routes use same agent | Complex custom logic |
| Want built-in loop control | Need fine-grained control |
| Want type-safe client rendering | Already working code |

---

### Your Code vs ToolLoopAgent

**Current** (~400 lines in route.ts):
- Manual `streamText` call
- Manual message handling
- Callbacks inline
- Tools defined separately

**With ToolLoopAgent** (~50 lines in route.ts):
- Agent defined once in `lib/agents/`
- Route just calls `createAgentUIStreamResponse`
- Type inference works automatically
- Easier testing (mock the agent)

